		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I find that LCD computer monitors generally have less lag than LCD TV sets, but computer monitors don't generally have composite input. However, if it is known being connected to NES/Famicom, then it might be possible to make some that converts in real-time into the picture which is being displayed perfectly without interlacing artifacts and so on.<br /><br />(In fact, I don't have a LCD TV. I use a LCD computer monitor (connected to a VCR/DVD combination, which also includes tuning) as a TV screen; devices can be connected to the composite input of the VCR, although it has a lot of lag so it isn't suitable for games; Wii games can connect directly to the monitor and run with no lag.)

		

